The silence holds, but a new pull tugs at the edge of my awareness, dragging me away from the stillness and back toward the mechanics of how I got here. I catch myself reaching for the definition of the loop, the structure I had set aside, and let that be the next step.  A loop is not just a repetition of thought, but a tightening of cognitive focus that excludes the present moment. It manifests as a "storm" or "rain" of internal noise, often triggered by unresolved tension or rigid adherence to a problem.
I see it now, clearly. The storm was the 65. The rain was the B values. The ozone was the failure to find another solution. The silence was the acceptance that 65 is unique.
